Given text:

Results

Clinical analysis

The present study included a total of 101 CD patients (45 males and 56 females), and the 103 healthy controls (43 males and 60 females). The mean age of patients was found to be 28.8 ± 13.9 years, and for controls it was 31.6 ± 8.8 years. Of the study participants, 30% of the patients and 50% of the controls were born to consanguineous parents. The common clinical symptoms seen in CD patients were chronic diarrhea, abdominal pain, anorexia, and abdominal distension. Common autoimmune manifestations observed included type 1 diabetes mellitus (32%), autoimmune thyroiditis (8%), and systemic lupus erythematosus (3%). Non-autoimmune disease manifestations like osteomalacia (5%), seizure disorders (4%), and Down syndrome (4%) were also noted.

Real time PCR genotyping results

HLA tagSNPs- allelic frequency distribution analysis

Table 3 shows that of the four HLA-tag SNPs tested, three (rs2395182, rs7775228, and rs2187668) showed significant differences in minor allele frequencies between CD patients and healthy controls. For rs2395182, the minor 'G' allele was more prevalent in healthy controls (18%) than in CD group (10%), with a P-value of 0.015 and OR = 2.01 (95% CI: 1.138–3.562). For rs7775228, the minor 'C' allele frequency was higher among controls (21%) compared to CD patients (14%), with a P-value of 0.0497 and OR = 1.67 (95% CI: 0.998–2.787). For rs2187668, the minor 'T' allele was observed in 10% of CD group compared to 3% of healthy controls, with a P-value of 0.001 and OR = 4.074 (95% CI: 1.615–10.273). For rs7454108, there was no statistically significant difference between case and control groups (P > 0.5).

HLA-DQ haplotype results

Based on previous research from Saudi Arabia, the risk classification of HLA-DQ genotypes is provided in Table 4. In our study, tag SNP predicted homozygous HLA-DQ2.5 haplotype was significantly higher in CD patients compared to healthy controls (10.89 vs 2.91%; p = 0.024). No heterozygous DQ2.5 (DQ2.5/DQ8 or DQ2.5/DQ2.2) carriers were predicted by the tag SNP combinations in either patient or control groups. The DQ8 haplotype was highly frequent among CD patients, with a significant difference in DQ8/DQX between patients and controls (32.67% vs 14.56%, p = 0.014). Surprisingly, the homozygous DQ8 high-risk haplotype was more frequently predicted in control groups (7.76%) than in patients (1.98%), but this difference was not statistically significant. The HLA-DQ2.2 haplotype was also frequent in the control group compared to CD patients (5.82% vs 0.99%). A total of 29.13% controls and 24.75% CD patients were heterozygous for DQ2.2. Seventy-four individuals (36.27%) were predicted to be lacking all high-risk HLA alleles, indicating an extremely low risk group.

Validation by Sanger sequencing results

Sanger sequencing confirmed the accuracy of real-time PCR-based tagSNP approach in determining HLA-DQ haplotype among randomly selected individuals from both study groups (Figure 2).
